The Revival of a Great Leader
LONDON —— It has been two centuries since the Battle of Waterloo, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-esteem to such an extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of it when writing the history of the French military.
Nevertheless, if you acknowledge that "greatness" is some kind of personal trait, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader" at all.
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "grotesque mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
According to Tolstoy, Napoleon was not an especially outstanding general; his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether or not Napoleon was great, we need to clarify whether we can describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can the leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his fellow German Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard "the rustling of the cloak of God."
Secondly, did the leader make important decisions?
Of course, if the leader was forced to make decisions, he or she could neither be blamed for them nor take credit for them.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the country.
Therefore, de Gaulle rightfully deserves a place on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-World War II decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country by suppressing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Similar to British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview and established their position in the global order after the war.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their nations' worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors viewed the world — and the role of their own countries — for many years afterward in ways that constrained rational discussion and distorted decision-making.
The result was that the leaders of the two countries afterwards were never able to achieve accomplishments that could be compared with those of the two great leaders.
However, there was still one British prime minister who could be compared with them: she was Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, with as many people who liked her as those who disliked her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago originated from resistance activities within her own cabinet and party.
But it is not necessary to be liked by everyone in order to be a great leader.
Indeed, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her influence.
Besides serving as the first female Prime Minister of the UK and nearly the earliest female Prime Minister in other countries, Thatcher helped turn around the UK's economic decline.
Moreover, her attacks on powerful unions enhanced the country's manageability at a time when it seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
In view of this, she undeniably has the right to be considered a candidate for "great leader".
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China is also qualified to be considered a great leader.
Apart from assisting Mao in doing evil, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen massacre.
But Deng simultaneously invigorated the market, leading China on an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately enabled hundreds of millions of Chinese people to escape poverty.
Many people regard Lee Kuan Yew, the founder of Singapore and long-serving Prime Minister, as a great leader, although he might have hoped to make an impact on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect whether a person can become a great leader.
I certainly had no intention of being disrespectful when I said that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially given that the political atmosphere in the country is generally not very contentious.
The United States is vast enough to be a birthplace for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not intellectual giants — demonstrated remarkable judgment in establishing the post-war international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed great talents — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy combined these talents.
He accomplished a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His ability to inspire was unparalleled; in fact, after his death, his assassination solidified the traditions he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure since the death of President Mandela, who combined courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charming and charismatic leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell — are either Africans or African Americans.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at first, but rarely made mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin when he invaded Ukraine and adopted a tolerant attitude towards the refugee crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders — those who exercise political power — can change the situation, whether for better or worse.
Merkel is today's most obvious example, showing Europe the way to cope with a difficult survival crisis.
